.TH "KRAMDOWN" 1 "July 2010"
.SH NAME
newstile \- a fast, pure-Ruby Markdown-superset converter
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B newstile
[\fIoptions\fR]
[\fIFILE\fR ...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
newstile is primarily used for parsing a superset of Markdown and converting it to different output
formats. It supports standard Markdown (with some minor modifications) and various extensions like
tables and definition lists. Due to its modular architecture it also allows other input formats than
Markdown, for example, HTML.

If \fIFILE\fR is not specified, newstile reads from the standard input. The result is written to the
standard output.

There are two sets of options that newstile accepts: The first one includes the options that are
used directly by the newstile binary. The second set of options controls how newstile parses and
converts its input.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-i, \-\-input ARG
Specify the input format. Available input formats: newstile (this is the default) or html.
.TP
.B \-o, \-\-output ARG
Specify the output format. Available output formats: html (this is the default), newstile or latex.
.TP
.B \-v, \-\-version
Show the version of newstile.
.TP
.B \-h, \-\-help
Show the help.

.SH KRAMDOWN OPTIONS
<%
require 'newstile/document'

Newstile::Options.definitions.each do |n, definition|
  n = n.to_s.tr('_', '-')
  if definition.type == Newstile::Options::Boolean %>
.TP
.B \-\-[no\-]<%= n %>
<% else
    next if definition.type == Object
    type = definition.type
    type = String if type == Symbol %>
.TP
.B \-\-<%= n %> ARG
<% end %>
<%= definition.desc %>
<% end %>
.SH EXIT STATUS
The exit status is 0 if no error happened. Otherwise it is 1.
